    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A confidentiality period defines how long the obligation to keep shared information secret remains active. In contrast, a survival clause specifies which contractual provisions, like confidentiality or indemnity, continue to be legally binding even after the main agreement has been terminated. Think of the confidentiality period as the *duration* of the secrecy, while the survival clause dictates *if* that secrecy obligation lasts past the contract's end date. It's crucial to check both to ensure your protections don't vanish unexpectedly.",
      "source": "target",
