    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I'm actually looking at a specific section right now regarding \"indemnification\" and \"third-party claims.\" Could you explain what that generally means for me as an individual, and if there are any sneaky ways those clauses can be used against someone?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Indemnification clauses essentially mean one party agrees to cover the losses or damages another party suffers due to specific actions or claims. If a third party sues you because of something related to this contract, the indemnifying party agrees to step in and cover your legal fees and any resulting judgments. A sneaky tactic is when the scope is too broad, forcing you to indemnify the other side for things that aren't actually your fault, like their own negligence. It's wise to ensure the clause only covers risks within your reasonable control.",
      "source": "target",
